Right now the only way to resolve an external function declared like
`static extern ReturnType FunctionName(Args...)` is to mark it with `DllImport` attribute, so that CLR would load this function from an external assembly.

I propose adding a new attribute, that could be used in place of `DllImport` which CLR should recognize, and whose behavior can be customized in managed code.

```csharp
public abstract class AbstractExternResolverAttribute: Attribute {
  public abstract MethodInfo /* or IntPtr */ Resolve(MethodInfo externMethod);
}
```

Which could later be used like this:
```csharp
public sealed class MyDllImportAttribute: AbstractExternResolverAttribute {
  readonly string libraryName;

  public MyDllImportAttribute(string libraryName) { this.libraryName = libraryName; }

  public override MethodInfo Resolve(MethodInfo externMethod) {
    // here we could do any custom probing for the library
    var library = NativeLibrary.Load(libraryName); 
    var export = library.GetFunction(externMethod.Name);
    var delegateType = ...;
    var @delegate = Marshal.GetDelegateForFunctionPointer(export, delegateType);
    return @delegate.Method;
  }
}
```

This would enable several things:
1. Fully customizable DLL search, which is a relatively common problem. #19112
2. Interfacing with exported functions from languages besides C. I could make a `CppExternResolverAttribute`, that would not only find the appropriate overload of the function given its signature, but could also generate a wrapper method, that would do parameter and result marshaling.
3. Enable some meta programming via reflection. Like deciding to use a native function vs a managed implementation without having to repeat the decision code. Or generating efficient method bodies based on value-typed generic argument.
4. (if possible) Having generic external functions and/or external functions in generic classes, that actually represent different functions for different type parameters. AFAIK it is possible for value types.

